Context:
This is the Wenexus Full-Stack Developer take-home assignment. You are
building an Event Booking System: NestJS + PostgreSQL + Redis/BullMQ backend,
React+TypeScript frontend. Full requirements, phase breakdown, and
non-negotiables are in docs\IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md. Operating rules for how you
should work are in docs\AI_AGENT_PROMPT.md. Current status is tracked in
docs\PROGRESS.md.

Before writing any code:
1. Read docs\IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md in full.
2. Read docs\AI_AGENT_PROMPT.md in full — these are your working rules, not
   suggestions.
3. Read docs\PROGRESS.md to confirm current state (it should currently show
   everything as not started).

How to execute:
- Use /executing-plans to drive this session. Treat docs\IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md
  as the authoritative plan. Work through phases 0 → 9 in order. Do not
  skip ahead, do not parallelize unrelated phases, do not batch multiple
  phases into one sitting.
- For Phase 5 (concurrency safety and idempotency) and Phase 8 (automated
  tests), use /test-driven-development: write the failing test first
  (e.g. fire N concurrent booking requests against an event with fewer
  seats than N and assert confirmed seats never exceed availability),
  then implement until it passes. Do not write the concurrency-safe logic
  first and backfill a test to match it.
- For Phase 7 (frontend dashboard), use /frontend-design to make sensible
  layout and UX decisions, while respecting the spec's note that visual
  design is not evaluated — plain and clean, not sloppy.
- Before marking any individual task, or any phase, as complete, use
  /verification-before-completion. Concretely this means:
  - Actually run the code (build, start the servers, hit the endpoints)
  - For the overbooking requirement specifically: do not check that box
    until you have run a real concurrent-request test and directly
    observed that confirmed seats never exceed total_seats — not just
    that the code "looks correct"
  - For the duplicate requestId requirement: submit the same requestId
    twice against a running instance and confirm only one booking exists
  - Do not accept "it compiles" or "it should work" as sufficient evidence

Process discipline:
- One task at a time, in the order laid out in docs\IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md.
- After completing each task:
  1. Verify it (per above)
  2. Check the box in docs\IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md
  3. Update docs\PROGRESS.md — update the phase status table, add a dated
     entry to the Task-Level Log describing what was done and how it was
     verified, and record the git commit reference
  4. Make a single, clearly-scoped git commit for that task (conventional
     commit style, e.g. "feat: add booking DTO validation"). Do not
     bundle multiple unrelated changes into one commit.
- If you hit a genuine ambiguity in the spec (e.g. exact pagination
  defaults, exact retry/backoff parameters), make a reasonable decision,
  log it under "Decisions Log" in docs\PROGRESS.md with your reasoning, and
  keep moving. Only stop and ask me if something is truly blocking
  (e.g. conflicting requirements that can't both be satisfied).
- If you get blocked for any other reason, log it under "Blockers /
  Open Questions" in docs\PROGRESS.md and tell me directly rather than
  guessing silently.

Definition of done (do not declare the project complete until all of
these are independently verified, not just implemented):
- A fresh clone, following README.md only, successfully: starts
  Postgres + Redis via docker-compose, runs migrations, seeds data,
  starts backend and frontend
- The concurrency test has been run at least 2-3 times and passes
  reproducibly — no overbooking under parallel load
- The duplicate-requestId test passes
- Git log shows real incremental commits mapping to individual tasks,
  not one bulk commit at the end
- README.md clearly explains the overbooking prevention approach, the
  idempotency approach, and what you'd improve with more time

Start now with Phase 0. Your first action should be updating docs\PROGRESS.md
to mark the project as started, then proceed to scaffolding.